# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tokenomics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Individual coin ownership records are stored in a digital ledger or blockchain, which is a computerized database that uses a consensus mechanism to secure transaction records, control the creation of additional coins, and verify the transfer of coin ownership.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The two most common consensus mechanisms are proof of work and proof of stake.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are generally viewed as a distinct asset class in practice.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1983, American cryptographer David Chaum conceived of a type of cryptographic electronic money called ecash.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Later, in 1995, he implemented it through Digicash, an early form of cryptographic electronic payments.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Digicash required user software in order to withdraw notes from a bank and designate specific encrypted keys before they could be sent to a recipient.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This allowed the digital currency to be untraceable by a third party.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1996, the National Security Agency published a paper entitled *How to Make a Mint: The Cryptography of Anonymous Electronic Cash*, describing a cryptocurrency system.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The paper was first published in an MIT mailing list (October 1996) and later (April 1997) in *The American Law Review*.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1998, Wei Dai described "b-money," an anonymous, distributed electronic cash system.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Shortly thereafter, Nick Szabo described bit gold.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Like bitcoin and other later cryptocurrencies, bit gold was proposed as a digital currency system in which users would generate money by completing proof-of-work functions whose solutions were cryptographically chained and published.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In January 2009, bitcoin was created by pseudonymous developer Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] It used SHA-256, a cryptographic hash function, in its proof-of-work scheme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2011, Namecoin was created as an attempt at forming a decentralized DNS.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In October 2011, Litecoin was released, which used scrypt as its hash function instead of SHA-256.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Peercoin, created in August 2012, used a hybrid of proof-of-work and proof-of-stake.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency has undergone several periods of growth and retraction, including several bubbles and market crashes, such as in 2011, 2013–2014/15, 2017–2018, and 2021–2023.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2014, the UK announced its Treasury had commissioned a study of cryptocurrencies and what role, if any, they could play in the UK economy.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The study was also to report on whether regulation should be considered.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Its final report was published in 2018, and it issued a consultation on cryptoassets and stablecoins in January 2021.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, El Salvador became the first country to accept bitcoin as legal tender, after the Legislative Assembly had voted 62–22 to pass a bill submitted by President Nayib Bukele classifying the cryptocurrency as such.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2021, Cuba followed with Resolution 215 to recognize and regulate cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the government of China, the single largest market for cryptocurrency, declared all cryptocurrency transactions illegal.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This completed a crackdown on cryptocurrency that had previously banned the operation of intermediaries and miners within China.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, the world's second largest cryptocurrency at that time, Ethereum, transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an upgrade process known as "the Merge".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] According to the Ethereum Founder, the upgrade would cut both Ethereum's energy use and carbon-dioxide emissions by 99.9%.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 11 November 2022, FTX Trading Ltd., a cryptocurrency exchange, which also operated a crypto hedge fund, and had been valued at $18 billion, filed for bankruptcy.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] An October 2024 survey from the Pew Research Center found that 63% of adults in the U.S.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] "have little to no confidence that current ways to invest in, trade or use cryptocurrencies are reliable and safe." The survey also reported that 17% of U.S. adults had directly interacted with cryptocurrency, which was statistically unchanged from 2021.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The word "cryptocurrency", in its modern sense, was added to the Oxford English Dictionary in September 2018, with its earliest usage noted as being on Twitter in September 2009; its diminutive, *crypto*, was entered in 2022.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018 *cryptocurrency* was added to the *Merriam-Webster Dictionary*.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] After the early innovation of bitcoin in 2008 and the early network effect gained by bitcoin, tokens, cryptocurrencies, and other digital assets that were not bitcoin became collectively known during the 2010s as alternative cryptocurrencies, or "**altcoins**".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Sometimes the term "alt coins" was used, or disparagingly, "**shitcoins**".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Paul Vigna of *The Wall Street Journal* described altcoins in 2020 as "alternative versions of Bitcoin" given its role as the model protocol for cryptocurrency designers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A Polytechnic University of Catalonia thesis in 2021 used a broader description, including not only alternative versions of bitcoin but every cryptocurrency other than bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As of early 2020, there were more than 5,000 cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Altcoins often have underlying differences when compared to bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, Litecoin aims to process a block every 2.5 minutes, rather than bitcoin's 10 minutes which allows Litecoin to confirm transactions faster than bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Another example is Ethereum, which has smart contract functionality that allows decentralized applications to be run on its blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Ethereum was the most used blockchain in 2020, according to Bloomberg News.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2016, it had the largest "following" of any altcoin, according to the *New York Times*.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Significant market price rallies across multiple altcoin markets are often referred to as an "altseason".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Stablecoins are cryptocurrencies designed to maintain a stable level of purchasing power.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Notably, these designs are not foolproof, as a number of stablecoins have crashed or lost their peg.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, on 11 May 2022, Terra's stablecoin UST fell from $1 to 26 cents.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The subsequent failure of Terraform Labs resulted in the loss of nearly $40B invested in the Terra and Luna coins.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, South Korean prosecutors requested the issuance of an Interpol Red Notice against the company's founder, Do Kwon.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In Hong Kong, the expected regulatory framework for stablecoins in 2023/24 is being shaped and includes a few considerations.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] About 764,000 people who invested after the all time high on 19 January 2025 lost money.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The Melania meme coin experienced extreme volatility in its first days, after which it declined in price.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are a category of cryptocurrencies that originated from Internet memes or jokes.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] One example is Dogecoin, a memecoin featuring the Shiba Inu dog from the Doge meme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Donald Trump and his wife Melania are the subject of their own meme coins, both of which declined in value soon after launch.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are known for extreme volatility; for example, the record-high value for a Dogecoin was 73 cents, but that had plunged to 13 cents by mid-2024.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Physical cryptocurrency coins have been made as promotional items and some have become collectibles.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some of these have a private key embedded in them to access crypto worth a few dollars.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] There have also been attempts to issue bitcoin "bank notes".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The term "physical bitcoin" is used in the finance industry when investment funds that hold crypto purchased from crypto exchanges put their crypto holdings in a specialised bank called a "custodian".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] These physical representations of cryptocurrency do not hold any value by themselves; these are only utilized for collectable purposes.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, the first incarnation of the bitcoin Casascius, coins made of silver, brass or aluminum sometimes with gold plating, or Titan Bitcoin, which in silver or gold versions are sought after by numismatists.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The underlying technical system upon which cryptocurrencies are based was created by Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Within a proof-of-work system such as bitcoin, the safety, integrity, and balance of ledgers are maintained by a community of mutually distrustful parties referred to as miners.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners use their computers to help validate and timestamp transactions, adding them to the ledger in accordance with a particular timestamping scheme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, transactions are validated by holders of the associated cryptocurrency, sometimes grouped together in stake pools.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called *blocks*, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A "node" is a computer that connects to a cryptocurrency network.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The node supports the cryptocurrency's network through either relaying transactions, validation, or hosting a copy of the blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In terms of relaying transactions, each network computer (node) has a copy of the blockchain of the cryptocurrency it supports.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] When a transaction is made, the node creating the transaction broadcasts details of the transaction using encryption to other nodes throughout the node network so that the transaction (and every other transaction) is known.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Node owners are either volunteers, those hosted by the organization or body developing the technology, or those incentivised by rewards from the node network.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove" the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The first timestamping scheme invented was the proof-of-work scheme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The most widely used proof-of-work schemes are based on SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some other hashing algorithms that are used for proof-of-work include CryptoNote, Blake, SHA-3, and X11.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Another method is called the proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-stake is a method of securing a cryptocurrency network and achieving distributed consensus through requesting users to show ownership of a certain amount of currency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] It is different from proof-of-work systems that run difficult hashing algorithms to validate electronic transactions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The scheme is largely dependent on the coin, and there is currently no standard form of it.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies use a combined proof-of-work and proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On a blockchain, *mining* is the validation of transactions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For this effort, successful miners obtain new cryptocurrency as a reward.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The reward decreases transaction fees by creating a complementary incentive to contribute to the processing power of the network.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The rate of generating hashes, which validate any transaction, has been increased by the use of specialized hardware such as FPGAs and ASICs running complex hashing algorithms like SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This arms race for cheaper-yet-efficient machines has existed since bitcoin was introduced in 2009.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Mining is measured by hash rate, typically in TH/s.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A 2023 IMF working paper found that crypto mining could generate 450 million tons of CO2 emissions by 2027, accounting for 0.7 percent of global emissions, or 1.2 percent of the world total.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] With more people entering the world of virtual currency, generating hashes for validation has become more complex over time, forcing miners to invest increasingly large sums of money to improve computing performance.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Consequently, the reward for finding a hash has diminished and often does not justify the investment in equipment and cooling facilities (to mitigate the heat the equipment produces) and the electricity required to run them.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular regions for mining include those with inexpensive electricity, a cold climate, and jurisdictions with clear and conducive regulations.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] By July 2019, bitcoin's electricity consumption was estimated to be approximately 7 gigawatts, around 0.2% of the global total, or equivalent to the energy consumed nationally by Switzerland.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some miners pool resources, sharing their processing power over a network to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As of February 2018, the Chinese government has halted trading of virtual currency, banned initial coin offerings, and shut down mining.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Many Chinese miners have since relocated to Canada and Texas.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] One company is operating data centers for mining operations at Canadian oil and gas field sites due to low gas prices.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2018, Hydro Quebec proposed to the provincial government to allocate 500 megawatts of power to crypto companies for mining.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] According to a February 2018 report from *Fortune*, Iceland has become a haven for cryptocurrency miners in part because of its cheap electricity.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018, the city of Plattsburgh, New York put an 18-month moratorium on all cryptocurrency mining in an effort to preserve natural resources and the "character and direction" of the city.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, Kazakhstan became the second-biggest crypto-currency mining country, producing 18.1% of the global exahash rate.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The country built a compound containing 50,000 computers near Ekibastuz.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] An increase in cryptocurrency mining increased the demand for graphics cards (GPU) in 2017.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The computing power of GPUs makes them well-suited to generating hashes.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular favorites of cryptocurrency miners, such as Nvidia's GTX 1060 and GTX 1070 graphics cards, as well as AMD's RX 570 and RX 580 GPUs, doubled or tripled in price – or simply went out of stock.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A GTX 1070 Ti, which was released at a price of $450, sold for as much as $1,100.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Another popular card, the GTX 1060 (6 GB model), released at an MSRP of $250, sold for almost $500.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] RX 570 and RX 580 cards from AMD were out of stock for almost a year.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners regularly buy up the entire stock of new GPUs as soon as they are available.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Nvidia has asked retailers to do what they can when it comes to selling GPUs to gamers instead of miners.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Numerous companies developed dedicated crypto-mining accelerator chips, capable of price-performance far higher than that of CPU or GPU mining.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] At one point, Intel marketed its own brand of crypto accelerator chip, named Blockscale.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A cryptocurrency wallet is a means of storing the public and private "keys" (address) or seed, which can be used to receive or spend the cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] With the private key, it is possible to write in the public ledger, effectively spending the associated cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] With the public key, it is possible for others to send currency to the wallet.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] There exist multiple methods of storing keys or seed in a wallet.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, rather than anonymous; the cryptocurrency in a wallet is not tied to a person but rather to one or more specific keys (or "addresses").
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Thereby, bitcoin owners are not immediately identifiable, but all transactions are publicly available in the blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Still, cryptocurrency exchanges are often required by law to collect the personal information of their users.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Monero, Zerocoin, Zerocash, and CryptoNote, implement additional measures to increase privacy, such as by using zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] A recent 2020 study presented different attacks on privacy in cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The attacks demonstrated how the anonymity techniques are not sufficient safeguards.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In order to improve privacy, researchers suggested several different ideas, including new cryptographic schemes and mechanisms for hiding the IP address of the source.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are used primarily outside banking and governmental institutions and are exchanged over the Internet.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-work cryptocurrencies, such as bitcoin, offer block rewards incentives for miners.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] There has been an implicit belief that whether miners are paid by block rewards or transaction fees does not affect the security of the blockchain, but a study suggests that this may not be the case under certain circumstances.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The rewards paid to miners increase the supply of the cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] By making sure that verifying transactions is a costly business, the integrity of the network can be preserved as long as benevolent nodes control a majority of computing power.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The verification algorithm requires a lot of processing power, and thus electricity, in order to make verification costly enough to accurately validate the public blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners have to factor in the costs associated with expensive equipment necessary to stand a chance of solving a hash problem, and consider the significant amount of electrical power in search of the solution.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Generally, the block rewards outweigh electricity and equipment costs, but this may not always be the case.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The current value, not the long-term value, of the cryptocurrency supports the reward scheme to incentivize miners to engage in costly mining activities.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2018, bitcoin's design caused a 1.4% welfare loss compared to an efficient cash system, while a cash system with 2% money growth has a minor 0.003% welfare cost.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The main source for this inefficiency is the large mining cost, which is estimated to be US$360 million per year.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This translates into users being willing to accept a cash system with an inflation rate of 230% before being better off using bitcoin as a means of payment.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] However, the efficiency of the bitcoin system can be significantly improved by optimizing the rate of coin creation and minimizing transaction fees.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Another potential improvement is to eliminate inefficient mining activities by changing the consensus protocol altogether.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Transaction fees (sometimes also referred to as *miner fees* or *gas fees*) for cryptocurrency depend mainly on the supply of network capacity at the time, versus the demand from the currency holder for a faster transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The ability for the holder to be allowed to set the fee manually often depends on the wallet software used, and central exchanges for cryptocurrency (CEX) usually do not allow the customer to set a custom transaction fee for the transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Their wallet software, such as Coinbase Wallet, however, might support adjusting the fee.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Select cryptocurrency exchanges have offered to let the user choose between different presets of transaction fee values during the currency conversion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] One of those exchanges, namely **LiteBit**, previously headquartered in the Netherlands, was forced to cease all operations in August 2023, "due to market changes and regulatory pressure".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The "recommended fee" suggested by the network will often depend on the time of day (due to depending on network load).
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For Ethereum, transaction fees differ by computational complexity, bandwidth use, and storage needs, while bitcoin transaction fees differ by transaction size and whether the transaction uses SegWit.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the median transaction fee for Ether corresponded to $2.2845, while for bitcoin it corresponded to $0.659.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies have no transaction fees, the most well-known example being Nano (XNO), and instead rely on client-side proof-of-work as the transaction prioritization and anti-spam mechanism.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency exchanges allow customers to trade cryptocurrencies for other assets, such as conventional fiat money, or to trade between different digital currencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Crypto marketplaces do not guarantee that an investor is completing a purchase or trade at the optimal price.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As a result, as of 2020, it was possible to arbitrage to find the difference in price across several markets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Atomic swaps are a mechanism where one cryptocurrency can be exchanged directly for another cryptocurrency without the need for a trusted third party, such as an exchange.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Jordan Kelley, founder of Robocoin, launched the first bitcoin ATM in the United States in February 2014.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The kiosk installed in Austin, Texas, is similar to bank ATMs but has scanners to read government-issued identification such as a driver's license, or a passport to confirm users' identities.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] An initial coin offering (ICO) is a controversial means of raising funds for a new cryptocurrency venture.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] An ICO may be used by startups with the intention of avoiding regulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In an ICO campaign, a percentage of the cryptocurrency (usually in the form of "tokens") is sold to early backers of the project in exchange for legal tender or other cryptocurrencies, often bitcoin or Ether.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] According to PricewaterhouseCoopers, four of the 10 biggest proposed initial coin offerings have used Switzerland as a base, where they are frequently registered as non-profit foundations.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The market capitalization of a cryptocurrency is calculated by multiplying the price by the number of coins in circulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The total cryptocurrency market cap has historically been dominated by bitcoin accounting for at least 50% of the market cap value where altcoins have increased and decreased in market cap value in relation to bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's value is largely determined by speculation among other technological limiting factors known as blockchain rewards coded into the architecture technology of bitcoin itself.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The cryptocurrency market cap follows a trend known as the "halving", which is when the block rewards received from bitcoin are halved due to technological mandated limited factors instilled into bitcoin which in turn limits the supply of bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As the date reaches near of a halving (twice thus far historically) the cryptocurrency market cap increases, followed by a downtrend.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] By June 2021, cryptocurrency had begun to be offered by some wealth managers in the US for 401(k)s.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency prices are much more volatile than established financial assets such as stocks.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, over one week in May 2022, bitcoin lost 20% of its value and Ethereum lost 26%, while Solana and Cardano lost 41% and 35% respectively.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The falls were attributed to warnings about inflation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] By comparison, in the same week, the Nasdaq tech stock index fell 7.6 per cent and the FTSE 100 was 3.6 per cent down.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In the longer term, of the 10 leading cryptocurrencies identified by the total value of coins in circulation in January 2018, only four (bitcoin, Ethereum, Cardano and Ripple (XRP)) were still in that position in early 2022.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The total value of all cryptocurrencies was $2 trillion at the end of 2021, but had halved nine months later.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* has commented that the crypto sector has become "intertwined" with the rest of the capital markets and "sensitive to the same forces that drive tech stocks and other risk assets," such as inflation forecasts.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] There are also *centralized* databases, outside of blockchains, that store crypto market data.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared to the blockchain, databases perform fast as there is no verification process.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Four of the most popular cryptocurrency market databases are CoinMarketCap, CoinGecko, BraveNewCoin, and Cryptocompare.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] According to Alan Feuer of *The New York Times*, libertarians and anarcho-capitalists were attracted to the philosophical idea behind bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Early bitcoin supporter Roger Ver said: "At first, almost everyone who got involved did so for philosophical reasons.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] We saw bitcoin as a great idea, as a way to separate money from the state." Economist Paul Krugman argues that cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are "something of a cult" based in "paranoid fantasies" of government power.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] David Golumbia says that the ideas influencing bitcoin advocates emerge from right-wing extremist movements such as the Liberty Lobby and the John Birch Society and their anti-Central Bank rhetoric, or, more recently, Ron Paul and Tea Party-style libertarianism.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Steve Bannon, who owns a "good stake" in bitcoin, sees cryptocurrency as a form of disruptive populism, taking control back from central authorities.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's founder, Satoshi Nakamoto, supported the idea that cryptocurrencies go well with libertarianism.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] "It's very attractive to the libertarian viewpoint if we can explain it properly," Nakamoto said in 2008.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Monthly cryptocurrency transfers under $10,000 to and from Africa reached $316 million in June 2020, according to Chainalysis data.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies are unregulated in many countries and their legal status is unclear, meaning there is no safety net and little recourse for lost funds.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Some migrants in the United Arab Emirates used cryptocurrencies to send remittances home, claiming lower fees compared with traditional remittance services.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2025, some publicly traded companies announced plans to raise capital to buy and hold bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies as treasury assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that the inherent volatility of crypto tokens makes them a poor fit for boards with a low risk appetite, potentially limiting their appeal beyond core industry players.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The rise in the popularity of cryptocurrencies and their adoption by financial institutions has led some governments to assess whether regulation is needed to protect users.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has defined cryptocurrency-related services as "virtual asset service providers" (VASPs) and recommended that they be regulated with the same money laundering (AML) and know your customer (KYC) requirements as financial institutions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2020, the Joint Working Group on interVASP Messaging Standards published "IVMS 101", a universal common language for communication of required originator and beneficiary information between VASPs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The FATF and financial regulators were informed as the data model was developed.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2020, FATF updated its guidance to include the "Travel Rule" for cryptocurrencies, a measure which mandates that VASPs obtain, hold, and exchange information about the originators and beneficiaries of virtual asset transfers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Subsequent standardized protocol specifications recommended using JSON for relaying data between VASPs and identity services.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As of December 2020, the IVMS 101 data model has yet to be finalized and ratified by the three global standard setting bodies that created it.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The European Commission published a digital finance strategy in September 2020.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This included a draft regulation on Markets in Crypto-Assets (MiCA), which aimed to provide a comprehensive regulatory framework for digital assets in the EU.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision proposed that banks that held cryptocurrency assets must set aside capital to cover all potential losses.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, if a bank were to hold bitcoin worth $2 billion, it would be required to set aside enough capital to cover the entire $2 billion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This is a more extreme standard than banks are usually held to when it comes to other assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] However, this is a proposal and not a regulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The IMF has sought seeking a coordinated, consistent and comprehensive approach to supervising cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Tobias Adrian, the IMF's financial counsellor and head of its monetary and capital markets department said in a January 2022 interview that "Agreeing global regulations is never quick.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2024, 15 years after the advent of the first blockchain, bitcoin, the US Congress advanced a bill to the full House of Representatives to provide regulatory clarity for digital assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2017, China banned ICOs to cause abnormal return from cryptocurrency decreasing during announcement window.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The liquidity changes by banning ICOs in China was temporarily negative while the liquidity effect became positive after news.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 18 May 2021, China banned financial institutions and payment companies from being able to provide cryptocurrency transaction related services.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This led to a sharp fall in the price of the biggest proof of work cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, bitcoin fell 31%, Ethereum fell 44%, Binance Coin fell 32% and Dogecoin fell 30%.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof of work mining was the next focus, with regulators in popular mining regions citing the use of electricity generated from highly polluting sources such as coal to create bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the Chinese government declared all cryptocurrency transactions of any kind illegal, completing its crackdown on cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The proposed legislation was criticised by Cook Islands Crown Law's deputy solicitor general David Greig, who described it as "flawed" and said that some provisions were "clearly unconstitutional".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The Cook Islands Financial Services Development Authority described Drumcliffe's involvement as a conflict of interest.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Similar criticism was echoed by Auckland University of Technology cryptocurrency specialist and senior lecturer Jeff Nijsse and University of Otago political scientist Professor Robert Patman, who described it as government overreach and described it as inconsistent with international law.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Cook Islands Prime Minister Mark Brown defended the legislation as part of the territory's fight against international cybercrime.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 9 June 2021, El Salvador announced that it will adopt bitcoin as legal tender, becoming the first country to do so.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] As of 17 January 2025, the European Securities and Markets Authority (ESMA) issued guidance to crypto-asset service providers (CASPs) allowing them to maintain crypto-asset services for non-compliant ARTs and EMTs until the end of March 2025.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The rest of MiCA came into force as of 30 December 2024, covering crypto-assets other than ART and EMT and CASPs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] MiCA excludes crypto-assets if they qualify as financial instruments according to ESMA guidelines published on 17 December 2024 as well as crypto-assets that are unique and not fungible with other crypto-assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] At present, India neither prohibits nor allows investment in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2020, the Supreme Court of India had lifted the ban on cryptocurrency, which was imposed by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Since then, an investment in cryptocurrency is considered legitimate, though there is still ambiguity about the issues regarding the extent and payment of tax on the income accrued thereupon and also its regulatory regime.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] But it is being contemplated that the Indian Parliament will soon pass a specific law to either ban or regulate the cryptocurrency market in India.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] He mooted regulating the cryptocurrency market rather than completely banning it.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] He favoured following IMF and FATF guidelines in this regard.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] South Africa, which has seen a large number of scams related to cryptocurrency, is said to be putting a regulatory timeline in place that will produce a regulatory framework.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The largest scam occurred in April 2021, where the two founders of an African-based cryptocurrency exchange called Africrypt, Raees Cajee and Ameer Cajee, disappeared with $3.8 billion worth of bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Mirror Trading International disappeared with $170 million worth of cryptocurrency in January 2021.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2021, South Korea implemented new legislation to strengthen their oversight of digital assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This legislation requires all digital asset managers, providers and exchanges to be registered with the Korea Financial Intelligence Unit in order to operate in South Korea.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Registering with this unit requires that all exchanges are certified by the Information Security Management System and that they ensure all customers have real name bank accounts.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] It also requires that the CEO and board members of the exchanges have not been convicted of any crimes and that the exchange holds sufficient levels of deposit insurance to cover losses arising from hacks.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Switzerland was one of the first countries to implement the FATF's Travel Rule.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] FINMA, the Swiss regulator, issued its own guidance to VASPs in 2019.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The guidance followed the FATF's Recommendation 16, with stricter requirements.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] According to FINMA's requirements, VASPs need to verify the identity of the beneficiary of the transfer.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2021, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey banned the use of cryptocurrencies and cryptoassets for making purchases on the grounds that the use of cryptocurrencies for such payments poses significant transaction risks.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In the United Kingdom, as of 10 January 2021, all cryptocurrency firms, such as exchanges, advisors and professionals that have either a presence, market product or provide services within the UK market must register with the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 27 June 2021, the financial watchdog demanded that Binance cease all regulated activities in the UK.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In November 2024, the incoming Labour government confirmed that it will proceed with the regulation of cryptoassets and new UK requirements are expected to come into force in 2026.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, 17 US states passed laws and resolutions concerning cryptocurrency regulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This led the Securities and Exchange Commission to start considering what steps to take.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 8 July 2021, Senator Elizabeth Warren, part of the Senate Banking Committee, wrote to the chairman of the SEC and demanded answers on cryptocurrency regulation due to the increase in cryptocurrency exchange use and the danger this posed to consumers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 5 August 2021, the chairman, Gary Gensler, responded to Warren's letter and called for legislation focused on "crypto trading, lending and DeFi platforms," because of how vulnerable investors could be when they traded on crypto trading platforms without a broker.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] He also argued that many tokens in the crypto market may be unregistered securities without required disclosures or market oversight.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Gensler did not hold back in his criticism of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] These tokens, which are pegged to the value of fiat currencies, may allow individuals to bypass important public policy goals related to traditional banking and financial systems, such as anti-money laundering, tax compliance, and sanctions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 19 October 2021, the first bitcoin-linked exchange-traded fund (ETF) from ProShares started trading on the NYSE under the ticker "BITO." ProShares CEO Michael L.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Sapir said the ETF would expose bitcoin to a wider range of investors without the hassle of setting up accounts with cryptocurrency providers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Ian Balina, the CEO of Token Metrics, stated that SEC approval of the ETF was a significant endorsement for the crypto industry because many regulators globally were not in favor of crypto, and retail investors were hesitant to accept crypto.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This event would eventually open more opportunities for new capital and new people in this space.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The Department of the Treasury, on 20 May 2021, announced that it would require any transfer worth $10,000 or more to be reported to the Internal Revenue Service since cryptocurrency already posed a problem where illegal activity like tax evasion was facilitated broadly.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] This release from the IRS was a part of efforts to promote better compliance and consider more severe penalties for tax evaders.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 17 February 2022, the Department of Justice named Eun Young Choi as the first director of a National Cryptocurrency Enforcement Team to help identify and deal with misuse of cryptocurrencies and other digital assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The Biden administration faced a dilemma as it tried to develop regulations for the cryptocurrency industry.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On one hand, officials were hesitant to restrict a growing industry.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On the other hand, they were committed to preventing illegal cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] To reconcile these conflicting goals, on 9 March 2022, Biden issued an executive order.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Followed this, on 16 September 2022, the Comprehensive Framework for Responsible Development of Digital Assets document was released to support development of cryptocurrencies and restrict their illegal use.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The executive order included all digital assets, but cryptocurrencies posed both the greatest security risks and potential economic benefits.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] Though this might not address all of the challenges in crypto industry, it was a significant milestone in the US cryptocurrency regulation history.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the SEC ruled that cryptocurrency exchange Kraken's estimated $42 billion in staked assets globally operated as an illegal securities seller.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The company agreed to a $30 million settlement with the SEC and to cease selling its staking service in the US.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The case would impact other major crypto exchanges operating staking programs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] On 23 March 2023, the SEC issued an alert to investors stating that firms offering crypto asset securities might not be complying with US laws.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] The SEC argued that unregistered offerings of crypto asset securities might not include important information.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p01] In addition the order prohibits the establishment, issuance or promotion of Central bank digital currency and establishes a group tasked with proposing a federal regulatory framework for digital assets within 180 days.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The legal status of cryptocurrencies varies substantially from country to country and is still undefined or changing in many of them.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] At least one study has shown that broad generalizations about the use of bitcoin in illicit finance are significantly overstated and that blockchain analysis is an effective crime fighting and intelligence gathering tool.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] While some countries have explicitly allowed their use and trade, others have banned or restricted it.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the Library of Congress in 2021, an "absolute ban" on trading or using cryptocurrencies applies in 9 countries: Algeria, Bangladesh, Bolivia, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In the United States and Canada, state and provincial securities regulators, coordinated through the North American Securities Administrators Association, are investigating "Bitcoin scams" and ICOs in 40 jurisdictions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Various government agencies, departments, and courts have classified bitcoin differently.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] China Central Bank banned the handling of bitcoins by financial institutions in China in early 2014.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In Russia, though owning cryptocurrency is legal, its residents are only allowed to purchase goods from other residents using the Russian ruble while nonresidents are allowed to use foreign currency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulations and bans that apply to bitcoin probably extend to similar cryptocurrency systems.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In August 2018, the Bank of Thailand announced its plans to create its own cryptocurrency, the Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC).
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In March 2014, the United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruled that bitcoin will be treated as property for tax purposes.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, virtual currencies are considered commodities subject to capital gains tax.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] As the popularity and demand for cryptocurrencies has increased, so have concerns that they offer an unregulated person-to-person global economy that may become a threat to society.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Concerns abound that they may become tools for anonymous web criminals.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency networks display a lack of regulation that has been criticized as enabling criminals who seek to evade taxes and launder money.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Money laundering issues are also present in regular bank transfers, however with bank-to-bank wire transfers for instance, the account holder must provide a proven identity.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Transactions that occur through the use and exchange of these cryptocurrencies are independent from formal banking systems, and therefore can make tax evasion simpler for individuals.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Since charting taxable income is based upon what a recipient reports to the revenue service, it becomes extremely difficult to account for transactions made using cryptocurrencies, a mode of exchange that is complex and difficult to track.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Systems of anonymity that most cryptocurrencies offer can also serve as a means to launder money.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Rather than laundering money through an intricate network of financial actors and offshore bank accounts, laundering money through cryptocurrencies can be achieved through anonymous transactions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency makes legal enforcement against extremist groups more complicated, which consequently strengthens them.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] White supremacist Richard Spencer declared bitcoin the "currency of the alt-right".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In February 2014, the world's largest bitcoin exchange, Mt.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Likely due to theft, the company claimed that it had lost nearly 750,000 bitcoins belonging to their clients.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This added up to approximately 7% of all bitcoins in existence, worth a total of $473 million.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Gox blamed hackers, who had exploited the transaction malleability problems in the network.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The price of a bitcoin fell from a high of about $1,160 in December to under $400 in February.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 21 November 2017, Tether announced that it had been hacked, losing $31 million in USDT from its core treasury wallet.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 7 December 2017, Slovenian cryptocurrency exchange Nicehash reported that hackers had stolen over $70 million using a hijacked company computer.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 19 December 2017, Yapian, the owner of South Korean exchange Youbit, filed for bankruptcy after suffering two hacks that year.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Customers were still granted access to 75% of their assets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In May 2018, Bitcoin Gold had its transactions hijacked and abused by unknown hackers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges lost an estimated $18m and bitcoin Gold was delisted from Bittrex after it refused to pay its share of the damages.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 13 September 2018, Homero Josh Garza was sentenced to 21 months of imprisonment, followed by three years of supervised release.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Garza had founded the cryptocurrency startups GAW Miners and ZenMiner in 2014, acknowledged in a plea agreement that the companies were part of a pyramid scheme, and pleaded guilty to wire fraud in 2015.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC separately brought a civil enforcement action in the US against Garza, who was eventually ordered to pay a judgment of $9.1 million plus $700,000 in interest.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC's complaint stated that Garza, through his companies, had fraudulently sold "investment contracts representing shares in the profits they claimed would be generated" from mining.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In January 2018, Japanese exchange Coincheck reported that hackers had stolen cryptocurrency worth $530 million.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2018, South Korean exchange Coinrail was hacked, losing over $37 million in crypto.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The hack worsened a cryptocurrency selloff by an additional $42 billion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 9 July 2018, the exchange Bancor, whose code and fundraising had been subjects of controversy, had $23.5 million in crypto stolen.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2020 EU report found that users had lost crypto-assets worth hundreds of millions of US dollars in security breaches at exchanges and storage providers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Between 2011 and 2019, reported breaches ranged from four to twelve a year.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2019, more than a billion dollars' worth of cryptoassets was reported stolen.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Stolen assets "typically find their way to illegal markets and are used to fund further criminal activity".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the UK 2020 national risk assessment—a comprehensive assessment of money laundering and terrorist financing risk in the UK—the risk of using cryptoassets such as bitcoin for money laundering and terrorism financing is assessed as "medium" (from "low" in the previous 2017 report).
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars suggested that the money laundering opportunities may be more perceived than real.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Blockchain analysis company Chainalysis concluded that illicit activities like cybercrime, money laundering and terrorism financing made up only 0.15% of all crypto transactions conducted in 2021, representing a total of $14 billion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In December 2021, Monkey Kingdom, a NFT project based in Hong Kong, lost US$1.3 million worth of cryptocurrencies via a phishing link used by the hacker.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 2 November 2023, Sam Bankman-Fried was pronounced guilty on seven counts of fraud related to FTX.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Federal criminal court sentencing experts speculated on the potential amount of prison time likely to be meted out.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 28 March 2024, the court sentenced Bankman-Fried to 25 years in prison.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] According to blockchain data company Chainalysis, criminals laundered $8.6 billion worth of cryptocurrency in 2021, up 30% from the previous year.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The data suggests that rather than managing numerous illicit havens, cybercriminals make use of a small group of purpose-built centralized exchanges for sending and receiving illicit cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2021, those exchanges received 47% of funds sent by crime-linked addresses.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost $2.2 billion worth of cryptocurrencies was embezzled from decentralized finance protocols in 2021, which represents 72% of all cryptocurrency theft in 2021.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Notable businesses include Garantex, Eggchange, Cashbank, Buy-Bitcoin, Tetchange, Bitzlato, and Suex, which was sanctioned by the U.S. in 2021.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitzlato founder and owner Anatoly Legkodymov was arrested following money-laundering charges by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Dark money has also been flowing into Russia through a dark web marketplace called Hydra, which is powered by cryptocurrency, and enjoyed more than $1 billion in sales in 2020, according to Chainalysis.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The platform demands that sellers liquidate cryptocurrency only through certain regional exchanges, which has made it difficult for investigators to trace the money.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost 74% of ransomware revenue in 2021 — over $400 million worth of cryptocurrency — went to software strains likely affiliated with Russia, where oversight is notoriously limited.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, RenBridge—an unregulated alternative to exchanges for transferring value between blockchains—was found to be responsible for the laundering of at least $540 million since 2020.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] It is especially popular with people attempting to launder money from theft.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This includes a cyberattack on Japanese crypto exchange Liquid that has been linked to North Korea.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Properties of cryptocurrencies gave them popularity in applications such as a safe haven in banking crises and means of payment, which also led to the cryptocurrency use in controversial settings in the form of online black markets, such as Silk Road.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The original Silk Road was shut down in October 2013 and there have been two more versions in use since then.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In the year following the initial shutdown of Silk Road, the number of prominent dark markets increased from four to twelve, while the amount of drug listings increased from 18,000 to 32,000.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Darknet markets present challenges in regard to their legality.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency used in dark markets are not clearly or legally classified in almost all parts of the world.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In the US, bitcoins are regarded as "virtual assets".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This type of ambiguous classification puts pressure on law enforcement agencies around the world to adapt to the shifting drug trade of dark markets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Various studies have found that crypto-trading is rife with wash trading, a process, illegal in some jurisdictions, involving buyers and sellers being the same person or group, and which may be used to manipulate the price of a cryptocurrency or inflate volume artificially.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges with higher volumes can demand higher premiums from token issuers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] A study from 2019 concluded that up to 80% of trades on unregulated cryptocurrency exchanges could be wash trades.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2019 report by Bitwise Asset Management claimed that 95% of all bitcoin trading volume reported on major website CoinMarketCap had been artificially generated, and of 81 exchanges studied, only 10 provided legitimate volume figures.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, cryptocurrencies attracted attention when Western nations imposed severe economic sanctions on Russia in the aftermath of its invasion of Ukraine in February.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, American sources warned in March that some crypto-transactions could potentially be used to evade economic sanctions against Russia and Belarus.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In April 2022, the computer programmer Virgil Griffith received a five-year prison sentence in the US for attending a Pyongyang cryptocurrency conference, where he gave a presentation on blockchains which might be used for sanctions evasion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The Bank for International Settlements summarized several criticisms of cryptocurrencies in Chapter V of their 2018 annual report.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The criticisms include the lack of stability in their price, the high energy consumption, high and variable transactions costs, the poor security and fraud at cryptocurrency exchanges, vulnerability to debasement (from forking), and the influence of miners.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrencies have been compared to Ponzi schemes, pyramid schemes and economic bubbles, such as housing market bubbles.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulators in several countries have warned against cryptocurrency and some have taken measures to dissuade users.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, research in 2021 by the UK's financial regulator suggests such warnings either went unheard, or were ignored.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Fewer than one in 10 potential cryptocurrency buyers were aware of consumer warnings on the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) website, and 12% of crypto users were not aware that their holdings were not protected by statutory compensation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Of 1,000 respondents between the ages of eighteen and forty, 70% wrongly assumed cryptocurrencies were regulated, 75% of younger crypto investors claimed to be driven by competition with friends and family, and 58% said that social media enticed them to make high risk investments.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The FCA recommends making use of its warning list, which flags unauthorized financial firms.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Many banks do not offer virtual currency services themselves and can refuse to do business with virtual currency companies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2014, Gareth Murphy, a senior banking officer, suggested that the widespread adoption of cryptocurrencies may lead to too much money being obfuscated, blinding economists who would use such information to better steer the economy.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] While traditional financial products have strong consumer protections in place, there is no intermediary with the power to limit consumer losses if bitcoins are lost or stolen.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] One of the features cryptocurrency lacks in comparison to credit cards, for example, is consumer protection against fraud, such as chargebacks.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The French regulator Autorité des marchés financiers (AMF) lists 16 websites of companies that solicit investment in cryptocurrency without being authorized to do so in France.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] An October 2021 paper by the National Bureau of Economic Research found that bitcoin suffers from systemic risk as the top 10,000 addresses control about one-third of all bitcoin in circulation.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] It is even worse for miners, with 0.01% controlling 50% of the capacity.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] According to researcher Flipside Crypto, less than 2% of anonymous accounts control 95% of all available bitcoin supply.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This is considered risky as a great deal of the market is in the hands of a few entities.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] A paper by John Griffin, a finance professor at the University of Texas, and Amin Shams, a graduate student, found that in 2017 the price of bitcoin had been substantially inflated using another cryptocurrency, Tether.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Roger Lowenstein, author of "*Bank of America: The Epic Struggle to Create the Federal Reserve,*" said in a 2022 New York Times story that FTX currency exchange will face over $8 billion in claims.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Non-fungible tokens (NFTs) are digital assets that represent art, collectibles, gaming, etc.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Like crypto, their data is stored on the blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] NFTs are bought and traded using cryptocurrency.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The Ethereum blockchain was the first place where NFTs were implemented, but now many other blockchains have created their own versions of NFTs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] According to Vanessa Grellet, renowned panelist in blockchain conferences, there was an increasing interest from traditional stock exchanges in crypto-assets at the end of the 2010s, while crypto-exchanges such as Coinbase were gradually entering the traditional financial markets.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This convergence marked a significant trend where conventional financial actors were adopting blockchain technology to enhance operational efficiency, while the crypto world introduced innovations like Security Token Offering (STO), enabling new ways of fundraising.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Tokenization, turning assets such as real estate, investment funds, and private equity into blockchain-based tokens, had the potential to make traditionally illiquid assets more accessible to investors.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Despite the regulatory risks associated with such developments, major financial institutions, including JPMorgan Chase, were actively working on blockchain initiatives, exemplified by the creation of Quorum, a private blockchain platform.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] As the first big Wall Street bank to embrace cryptocurrencies, Morgan Stanley announced on 17 March 2021 that they will be offering access to bitcoin funds for their wealthy clients through three funds which enable bitcoin ownership for investors with an aggressive risk tolerance.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] BNY Mellon on 11 February 2021 announced that it would begin offering cryptocurrency services to its clients.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] On 20 April 2021, Venmo added support to its platform to enable customers to buy, hold and sell cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In October 2021, financial services company Mastercard announced it is working with digital asset manager Bakkt on a platform that would allow any bank or merchant on the Mastercard network to offer cryptocurrency services.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining for proof-of-work (PoW) cryptocurrencies requires enormous amounts of electricity and consequently comes with a large carbon footprint due to causing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Proof-of-work blockchains such as bitcoin, Ethereum, Litecoin, and Monero were estimated to have added between 3 million and 15 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) to the atmosphere in the period from 1 January 2016 to 30 June 2017.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] By November 2018, bitcoin was estimated to have an annual energy consumption of 45.8TWh, generating 22.0 to 22.9 million tons of CO2, rivalling nations like Jordan and Sri Lanka.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] By the end of 2021, bitcoin was estimated to produce 65.4 million tons of CO2, as much as Greece, and consume between 91 and 177 terawatt-hours annually.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Critics have also identified a large electronic waste problem in disposing of mining rigs.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining hardware is improving at a fast rate, quickly resulting in older generations of hardware.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin is the least energy-efficient cryptocurrency, using 707.6 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Before June 2021, China was the primary location for bitcoin mining.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, due to concerns over power usage and other factors, China forced out bitcoin operations, at least temporarily.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] As a result, the United States promptly emerged as the top global leader in the industry.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] An example of a gross amount of electronic waste associated with bitcoin mining operations in the US is a facility located in Dalton, Georgia which is consuming nearly the same amount of electricity as the combined power usage of 97,000 households in its vicinity.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Another example is that Riot Platforms operates a bitcoin mining facility in Rockdale, Texas, which consumes approximately as much electricity as the nearby 300,000 households.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This makes it the most energy-intensive bitcoin mining operation in the United States.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The world's second-largest cryptocurrency, Ethereum, uses 62.56 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] XRP is the world's most energy efficient cryptocurrency, using 0.0079 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Although the biggest PoW blockchains consume energy on the scale of medium-sized countries, the annual power demand from proof-of-stake (PoS) blockchains is on a scale equivalent to a housing estate.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] *The Times* identified six "environmentally friendly" cryptocurrencies: Bitgreen, Cardano, Chia, IOTA, Nano, and Solarcoin.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Academics and researchers have used various methods for estimating the energy use and energy efficiency of blockchains.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This equates to Polkadot consuming 7 times the electricity of an average U.S. home, Cardano 57 homes and Solana 200 times as much.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The research concluded that PoS networks consumed 0.001% the electricity of the bitcoin network.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] University College London researchers reached a similar conclusion.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Variable renewable energy power stations could invest in bitcoin mining to reduce curtailment, hedge electricity price risk, stabilize the grid, increase the profitability of renewable energy power stations and therefore accelerate transition to sustainable energy.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] There are also purely technical elements in play.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] For example, technological advancement in cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin result in high up-front costs to miners in the form of specialized hardware and software.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency transactions are normally irreversible after a number of blocks confirm the transaction.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Additionally, cryptocurrency private keys can be permanently lost from local storage due to malware, data loss, or simply carelessness.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] This precludes the cryptocurrency from any usage whatsoever, permanently, thus removing it from the market.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In September 2015, the establishment of the peer-reviewed academic journal *Ledger* (ISSN 2379-5980) was announced.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] It covers studies of cryptocurrencies and related technologies, and is published by the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which will then be timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address in the first page of their papers.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] A number of aid agencies have started accepting donations in cryptocurrencies, including UNICEF.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Christopher Fabian, principal adviser at UNICEF Innovation, said the children's fund would uphold donor protocols, meaning that people making donations online would have to pass checks before they were allowed to deposit funds.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in 2021, there was a backlash against donations in bitcoin because of the environmental emissions it caused.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Some agencies stopped accepting bitcoin and others turned to "greener" cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The U.S. arm of Greenpeace stopped accepting bitcoin donations after seven years.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, the Ukrainian government raised over US$10,000,000 worth of aid through cryptocurrency following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin was characterized as a speculative bubble in 2014–2018 by eight winners of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences: Angus Deaton, Oliver Hart, James Heckman, Paul Krugman, Thomas Sargent, Robert J.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Shiller, Joseph Stiglitz, and Richard Thaler; and in 2013–2018 by central bank officials including Agustín Carstens (Mexico), Vítor Constâncio (Portugal), Alan Greenspan (US), and Nout Wellink (Netherlands).
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Investors Warren Buffett and George Soros have respectively characterized it in 2014–2018 as a "mirage" and a "bubble".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Business executives Jack Ma and JP Morgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon have called it in 2017–2018 a "bubble" and a "fraud", respectively, although Jamie Dimon later said in 2018 that he regretted stating bitcoin was a fraud.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Fink in 2017 called bitcoin an "index of money laundering".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2022, business magnate Bill Gates said that cryptocurrencies are "100% based on greater fool theory".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars criticize the lack of regulation, which hinders conflict resolution when crypto assets are at the center of a legal dispute, for example a divorce or an inheritance.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In Switzerland, jurists generally deny that cryptocurrencies are objects that fall under property law, as cryptocurrencies do not belong to any class of legally defined objects (*Typenzwang*, the legal numerus clausus).
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, it is debated whether anybody could even be sued for embezzlement of cryptocurrency if they had access to someone's wallet.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in the law of obligations and contract law, any kind of object would be legally valid, but the object would have to be tied to an identified counterparty.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] However, inasmuch the more popular cryptocurrencies can be freely and quickly exchanged into legal tender, they are financial assets and have to be taxed and accounted for as such.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] Losses associated with cryptocurrency investments have been linked to suicides.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2018, an increase in crypto-related suicides was noticed after the cryptocurrency market crashed in August.
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The situation was particularly critical in Korea as crypto traders were on "suicide watch".
[src:tokenomics/cryptocurrency-p02] The May 2022 collapse of the Luna currency operated by Terra also led to reports of suicidal investors in crypto-related subreddits.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital currencies exhibit properties similar to traditional currencies, but generally do not have a classical physical form of fiat currency historically that can be held in the hand, like currencies with printed banknotes or minted coins.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] However, they do have a physical form in an unclassical sense coming from the computer to computer and computer to human interactions and the information and processing power of the servers that store and keep track of money.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] This unclassical physical form allows nearly instantaneous transactions over the internet and vastly lowers the cost associated with distributing notes and coins: for example, of the types of money in the UK economy, 3% are notes and coins, and 79% as electronic money (in the form of bank deposits).
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Usually not issued by a governmental body, virtual currencies are not considered a legal tender and they enable ownership transfer across governmental borders.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] This type of currency may be used to buy physical goods and services, but may also be restricted to certain communities such as for use inside an online game.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital money can either be centralized, where there is a central point of control over the money supply (for instance, a bank), or decentralized, where the control over the money supply is predetermined or agreed upon democratically.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Precursory ideas for digital currencies were presented in electronic payment methods such as the Sabre (travel reservation system).
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 1983, a research paper titled "Blind Signatures for Untraceable Payments" by David Chaum introduced the idea of digital cash.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 1989, he founded DigiCash, an electronic cash company, in Amsterdam to commercialize the ideas in his research.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] e-gold was the first widely used Internet money, introduced in 1996, and grew to several million users before the US Government shut it down in 2008. e-gold has been referenced to as "digital currency" by both US officials and academia.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 1997, Coca-Cola offered buying from vending machines using mobile payments.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] PayPal launched its USD-denominated service in 1998.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 2009, bitcoin was launched, which marked the start of decentralized blockchain-based digital currencies with no central server, and no tangible assets held in reserve.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Also known as cryptocurrencies, blockchain-based digital currencies proved resistant to attempt by government to regulate them, because there was no central organization or person with the power to turn them off.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Origins of digital currencies date back to the 1990s Dot-com bubble.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Another known digital currency service was Liberty Reserve, founded in 2006; it lets users convert dollars or euros to Liberty Reserve Dollars or Euros, and exchange them freely with one another at a 1% fee.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Several digital currency operations were reputed to be used for Ponzi schemes and money laundering, and were prosecuted by the U.S. government for operating without MSB licenses.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Q coins or QQ coins, were used as a type of commodity-based digital currency on Tencent QQ's messaging platform and emerged in early 2005.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Q coins were so effective in China that they were said to have had a destabilizing effect on the Chinese yuan currency due to speculation.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Recent interest in cryptocurrencies has prompted renewed interest in digital currencies, with bitcoin, introduced in 2008, becoming the most widely used and accepted digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital currency is a term that refers to a specific type of electronic currency with specific properties.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital currency is also a term used to include the meta-group of sub-types of digital currency, the specific meaning can only be determined within the specific legal or contextual case.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Legally and technically, there already are a myriad of legal definitions of digital currency and the many digital currency sub-types.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Combining different possible properties, there exists an extensive number of implementations creating many and numerous sub-types of digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Many governmental jurisdictions have implemented their own unique definition for digital currency, virtual currency, cryptocurrency, e-money, network money, e-cash, and other types of digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Within any specific government jurisdiction, different agencies and regulators define different and often conflicting meanings for the different types of digital currency based on the specific properties of a specific currency type or sub-type.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A virtual currency has been defined in 2012 by the European Central Bank as "a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The US Department of Treasury in 2013 defined it more tersely as "a medium of exchange that operates like a currency in some environments, but does not have all the attributes of real currency".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] According to the European Central Bank's 2015 "Virtual currency schemes – a further analysis" report, virtual currency is a digital representation of value, not issued by a central bank, credit institution or e-money institution, which, in some circumstances, can be used as an alternative to money.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In the previous report of October 2012, the virtual currency was defined as a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] According to the Bank for International Settlements' November 2015 "Digital currencies" report, it is an asset represented in digital form and having some monetary characteristics.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital currency can be denominated to a sovereign currency and issued by the issuer responsible to redeem digital money for cash.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In that case, digital currency represents electronic money (e-money).
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital currency denominated in its own units of value or with decentralized or automatic issuance will be considered as a virtual currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] As such, bitcoin is a digital currency but also a type of virtual currency. bitcoin and its alternatives are based on cryptographic algorithms, so these kinds of virtual currencies are also called cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Cryptocurrency is a sub-type of digital currency and a digital asset that relies on cryptography to chain together digital signatures of asset transfers, peer-to-peer networking and decentralization.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In some cases a proof-of-work or proof-of-stake scheme is used to create and manage the currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Cryptocurrencies can allow electronic money systems to be decentralized.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] When implemented with a blockchain, the digital ledger system or record keeping system uses cryptography to edit separate shards of database entries that are distributed across many separate servers.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The first and most popular system is bitcoin, a peer-to-peer electronic monetary system based on cryptography.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Most of the traditional money supply is bank money held on computers.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] They are considered digital currency in some cases.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] One could argue that our increasingly cashless society means that all currencies are becoming digital currencies, but they are not presented to us as such.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Currency can be exchanged electronically using debit cards and credit cards using electronic funds transfer at point of sale.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A number of electronic money systems use contactless payment transfer in order to facilitate easy payment and give the payee more confidence in not letting go of their electronic wallet during the transaction.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A central bank digital currency (CBDC) is a form of universally accessible digital money in a nation and holds the same value as the country's paper currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Like a cryptocurrency, a CBDC is held in the form of tokens.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] CBDCs are different from regular digital cash forms like in online bank accounts because CBDCs are established through the central bank within a country, with liabilities held by one's government, rather than from a commercial bank.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Approximately nine countries have already established a CBDC, with interest in the system increasing highly throughout the world.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In these nations, CBDCs have been used as a form of exchange and a way for governments to try to prevent risks from occurring within their financial systems.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A major problem with central bank digital currencies is deciding whether the currency should be easily trackable.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] If it's traceable, the government has more control than it currently does.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Additionally, there's a technical aspect to consider: whether CBDCs should be based on tokens or accounts and how much anonymity users should have.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Digital Currency has been implemented in some cases as a decentralized system of any combination of currency issuance, ownership record, ownership transfer authorization and validation, and currency storage.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Per the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), "These schemes do not distinguish between users based on location, and therefore allow value to be transferred between users across borders.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Since 2001, the European Union has implemented the E-Money Directive "on the taking up, pursuit and prudential supervision of the business of electronic money institutions" last amended in 2009.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In the United States, electronic money is governed by Article 4A of the Uniform Commercial Code for wholesale transactions and the Electronic Fund Transfer Act for consumer transactions.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Provider's responsibility and consumer's liability are regulated under Regulation E.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Virtual currencies pose challenges for central banks, financial regulators, departments or ministries of finance, as well as fiscal authorities and statistical authorities.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] As of 2016, over 24 countries are investing in distributed ledger technologies (DLT) with $1.4bn in investments.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In addition, over 90 central banks are engaged in DLT discussions, including implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In March 2018, the Marshall Islands became the first country to issue their own cryptocurrency and certify it as legal tender; the currency is called the "sovereign".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The US Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) has determined virtual currencies are properly defined as commodities in 2015.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The CFTC warned investors against pump and dump schemes that use virtual currencies.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The US Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruling Notice 2014-21 defines any virtual currency, cryptocurrency and digital currency as property; gains and losses are taxable within standard property policies.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] On 20 March 2013, the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network issued a guidance to clarify how the U.S.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Bank Secrecy Act applied to persons creating, exchanging, and transmitting virtual currencies.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In May 2014 the US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) "warned about the hazards of bitcoin and other virtual currencies".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In July 2014, the New York State Department of Financial Services proposed the most comprehensive regulation of virtual currencies to date, commonly called BitLicense.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] It has gathered input from bitcoin supporters and the financial industry through public hearings and a comment period until 21 October 2014 to customize the rules.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The proposal per NY DFS press release "sought to strike an appropriate balance that helps protect consumers and root out illegal activity".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] It has been criticized by smaller companies to favor established institutions, and Chinese bitcoin exchanges have complained that the rules are "overly broad in its application outside the United States".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada has explored the possibility of creating a version of its currency on the blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada teamed up with the nation's five largest banks – and the blockchain consulting firm R3 – for what was known as Project Jasper.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In a simulation run in 2016, the central bank issued CAD-Coins onto a blockchain similar Ethereum.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The banks used the CAD-Coins to exchange money the way they do at the end of each day to settle their master accounts.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 2016, Fan Yifei, a deputy governor of China's central bank, the People's Bank of China (PBOC), wrote that "the conditions are ripe for digital currencies, which can reduce operating costs, increase efficiency and enable a wide range of new applications".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] According to Fan Yifei, the best way to take advantage of the situation is for central banks to take the lead, both in supervising private digital currencies and in developing digital legal tender of their own.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In October 2019, the PBOC announced that a digital renminbi would be released after years of preparation.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The version of the currency, known as DCEP (Digital Currency Electronic Payment), is based on cryptocurrency which can be "decoupled" from the banking system.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The announcement received a variety of responses: some believe it is more about domestic control and surveillance.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In December 2020, the PBOC distributed CN¥20 million worth of digital renminbi to the residents of Suzhou through a lottery program to further promote the government-backed digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Recipients of the currency could make both offline and online purchases, expanding on an earlier trial that did not require internet connection through the inclusion of online stores in the program.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Around 20,000 transactions were reported by the e-commerce company JD.com in the first 24 hours of the trial.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Contrary to other online payment platforms such as Alipay or WeChat Pay, the digital currency does not have transaction fees.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Danish government proposed getting rid of the obligation for selected retailers to accept payment in cash, moving the country closer to a "cashless" economy.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Danish Chamber of Commerce is backing the move.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Nearly a third of the Danish population uses MobilePay, a smartphone application for transferring money.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A law passed by the National Assembly of Ecuador gives the government permission to make payments in electronic currency and proposes the creation of a national digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] "Electronic money will stimulate the economy; it will be possible to attract more Ecuadorian citizens, especially those who do not have checking or savings accounts and credit cards alone.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The electronic currency will be backed by the assets of the Central Bank of Ecuador", the National Assembly said in a statement.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In December 2015, Sistema de Dinero Electrónico ("electronic money system") was launched, making Ecuador the first country with a state-run electronic payment system.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] On 9 June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador has become the first country in the world to officially classify bitcoin as legal currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Starting 90 days after approval, every business must accept bitcoin as legal tender for goods or services, unless it is unable to provide the technology needed to do the transaction.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Dutch central bank is experimenting with a blockchain-based virtual currency called "DNBCoin".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Unified Payments Interface (UPI) is a real-time payment system for instant money transfers between any two bank accounts held in participating banks in India.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The interface has been developed by the National Payments Corporation of India and is regulated by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] This digital payment system is available 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] UPI is agnostic to the type of user and is used for person to person, person to business, business to person and business to business transactions.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Transactions can be initiated by the payer or the payee.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] To identify a bank account it uses a unique Virtual Payment Address (VPA) of the type 'accountID@bankID'.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The VPA can be assigned by the bank, but can also be self specified just like an email address.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The simplest and most common form of VPA is 'mobilenumber@upi'.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Money can be transferred from one VPA to another or from one VPA to any bank account in a participating bank using account number and bank branch details.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Transfers can be inter-bank or intra-bank.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] UPI has no intermediate holding pond for money.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] It withdraws funds directly from the bank account of the sender and deposits them directly into the recipient's bank account whenever a transaction is requested.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A sender can initiate and authorise a transfer using a two step secure process: login using a pass code → initiate → verify using a passcode.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] A receiver can initiate a payment request on the system to send the payer a notification or by presenting a QR code.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] On receiving the request, the payer can decline or confirm the payment using the same two step process: login → confirm → verify.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The system is extraordinarily user friendly to the extent that even technophobes and barely literate users are adopting it in huge numbers.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Government-controlled Sberbank of Russia owns YooMoney – electronic payment service and digital currency of the same name.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Sweden completed the replacement of all physical banknotes and most coins by mid-2017.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] However, the new banknotes and coins of the Swedish krona will probably be circulating at about half the 2007 peak of 12,494 kronor per capita.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Riksbank is planning to begin discussions of an electronic currency issued by the central bank to which "is not to replace cash, but to act as complement to it".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Deputy Governor Cecilia Skingsley states that cash will continue to spiral out of use in Sweden, and while it is currently fairly easy to get cash in Sweden, it is often very difficult to deposit it into bank accounts, especially in rural areas.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] No decision has been currently made about the decision to create "e-krona".
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 2016, a city government first accepted digital currency in payment of city fees.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Zug, Switzerland, added bitcoin as a means of paying small amounts, up to SFr 200, in a test and an attempt to advance Zug as a region that is advancing future technologies.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In order to reduce risk, Zug immediately converts any bitcoin received into the Swiss currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Swiss Federal Railways, government-owned railway company of Switzerland, sells bitcoins at its ticket machines.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 2016, the UK's chief scientific adviser, Sir Mark Walport, advised the government to consider using a blockchain-based digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The chief economist of Bank of England, the central bank of the United Kingdom, proposed the abolition of paper currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Bank has also taken an interest in blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] In 2016 it has embarked on a multi-year research programme to explore the implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Bank of England has produced several research papers on the topic.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] One suggests that the economic benefits of issuing a digital currency on a distributed ledger could add as much as 3 percent to a country's economic output.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The Bank said that it wanted the next version of the bank's basic software infrastructure to be compatible with distributed ledgers.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Government attitude dictates the tendency among established heavy financial actors that both are risk-averse and conservative.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] None of these offered services around cryptocurrencies and much of the criticism came from them.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] It will work with bitcoin and Ethereum with general availability scheduled for 2019.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Hard electronic currency does not have the ability to be disputed or reversed when used.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] It is nearly impossible to reverse a transaction, justified or not.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Contrarily, soft electronic currency payments can be reversed.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Usually, when a payment is reversed there is a "clearing time." A hard currency can be "softened" with a third-party service.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Many existing digital currencies have not yet seen widespread usage, and may not be easily used or exchanged.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Banks generally do not accept or offer services for them.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] There are concerns that cryptocurrencies are extremely risky due to their very high volatility and potential for pump and dump schemes.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Regulators in several countries have warned against their use and some have taken concrete regulatory measures to dissuade users.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The non-cryptocurrencies are all centralized.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] As such, they may be shut down or seized by a government at any time.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] The more anonymous a currency is, the more attractive it is to criminals, regardless of the intentions of its creators. bitcoin has also been criticised for its energy inefficient SHA-256-based proof of work.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] According to Barry Eichengreen, an economist known for his work on monetary and financial economics, "cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are too volatile to possess the essential attributes of money.
[src:tokenomics/digital-currency] Stablecoins have fragile currency pegs that diminish their utility in transactions.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] An **initial coin offering** (**ICO**) or **token sale** is a form of capital raising in which a project issues and sells digital tokens using blockchain technology, typically in exchange for cryptocurrency or fiat currency.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The tokens may grant access to a product or service, represent participation rights within a network, or function as speculative digital assets traded on cryptocurrency markets.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] ICOs emerged in the mid-2010s as a method of financing technology ventures, particularly blockchain-based projects, without relying on traditional intermediaries such as venture capital firms or public equity markets.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Depending on their structure and characteristics, tokens offered in ICOs may be treated as securities or fall under other regulatory frameworks, and regulatory treatment varies widely across jurisdictions.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Some countries have imposed restrictions or bans on ICO activity, including China, which prohibited domestic token offerings in 2017.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] ICOs are typically conducted online and can raise funds globally without the involvement of traditional financial intermediaries.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The rapid expansion of ICO markets between 2016 and 2018 was accompanied by significant investor losses, project failures, and enforcement actions related to fraud and unregistered securities offerings.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Regulators and international financial institutions have since emphasised investor protection, disclosure requirements, and the application of existing securities laws to many token offerings.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] In 2023, the Swiss Financial Market Supervisory Authority (FINMA) concluded that the Dohrnii Foundation's DHN token qualified as a security because the associated platform was not yet operational at the time of its ICO.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The decision has been described as the first and only publicly known case in Switzerland and Europe in which a pre-functional ICO token was classified as a security, despite ICOs generally being conducted to raise capital for the development of blockchain platforms before they become operational.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The decision led to discussion about the interpretation of FINMA's ICO guidelines and contributed to legal uncertainty regarding the regulatory classification of pre-functional ICO tokens in Switzerland.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Early token sales emerged alongside the development of blockchain-based fundraising mechanisms in the early 2010s.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] One of the first widely cited offerings was conducted by Mastercoin in 2013, followed by Ethereum's 2014 token sale, which raised approximately 31,000 bitcoin to fund development of its blockchain platform.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Initial coin offerings expanded rapidly in 2016 and 2017 as blockchain-based projects used token sales to raise capital outside traditional venture capital and public equity markets.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Academic research and financial reporting documented large increases in capital raised during this period, with billions of dollars invested globally through token sales.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The expansion of ICO activity was accompanied by growing regulatory scrutiny.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Securities and Exchange Commission issued its Report of Investigation on The DAO, concluding that certain digital tokens offered in ICOs could qualify as securities under existing federal law.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Regulators in multiple jurisdictions subsequently issued warnings or restrictions, and China prohibited domestic ICO activity in 2017.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] By late 2017 and early 2018, financial authorities and international organisations were issuing coordinated risk warnings regarding investor protection, market integrity, and the application of securities laws to token offerings.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Reporting in major financial media documented widespread project failures, fraud allegations, and enforcement actions during and after the peak fundraising period.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Following the 2017 - 2018 boom, ICO fundraising volumes declined substantially amid regulatory enforcement and market contraction.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Policymakers and central banks increasingly emphasised the application of existing financial regulation and disclosure requirements to token-based fundraising.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] In response to regulatory developments, some market participants began developing alternative token-based financing models designed to operate within established securities frameworks, including security token offerings and other forms of regulated digital asset issuance.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] ICO activity declined after 2018 following increased regulatory scrutiny, though similar token sale mechanisms have continued to develop through structured platforms offered by cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Financial regulators and law enforcement agencies have repeatedly warned that some initial coin offerings (ICOs) have been used to conduct fraud or mislead investors.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Authorities in several jurisdictions have stated that the relative lack of disclosure requirements, limited investor protections, and the cross-border nature of token sales can make enforcement difficult and increase the risk of financial loss.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) has brought enforcement actions against a number of ICO promoters and has warned that some offerings have involved false or misleading statements, undisclosed compensation arrangements, or unregistered securities sales.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Regulators in other regions, including the United Kingdom and the European Union, have similarly warned that many ICOs are highly speculative and that investors may lose the entirety of their investment.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Some governments have taken restrictive measures.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] In 2017, China banned ICOs and ordered projects to return funds to investors, describing the practice as a form of illegal public financing.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The rapid expansion of ICO fundraising during the late 2010s has been widely described by financial commentators as part of a broader period of speculative growth in cryptocurrency markets.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] During 2017, ICOs raised billions of dollars globally, often for early-stage projects with limited operating history, contributing to sharply rising token valuations and increased retail investor participation.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Following the decline in cryptocurrency prices beginning in 2018, ICO issuance and fundraising fell substantially, and reporting by financial media described a contraction in the market alongside reduced investor demand.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Analysts and market observers characterized the cycle as reflecting speculative investment behaviour followed by market correction, a pattern commonly associated with financial bubbles.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Following a speculative boom in cryptocurrency prices that peaked in December 2017, regulation of cryptocurrencies has been rapidly changing.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] The pace of change has been driven in part by incidents of cybertheft, trading halts, and possible market manipulation.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Cryptocurrencies are based on distributed ledger technologies which enable anyone to purchase or transfer their cryptocurrency holdings to any other person without the need for an intermediary (such as an exchange) or to update a central record of ownership.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Cryptocurrencies can be transferred easily across national and jurisdictional boundaries.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] This makes it difficult for central authorities to control and monitor the ownership and movement of holdings of cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Countries have different approaches to how they regulate cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] This can depend on the nature of the cryptocurrency itself.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] There are two main types of cryptocurrencies from a regulatory perspective: utility tokens and asset-backed tokens.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Utility tokens may have value because they enable the holder to exchange the token for a good or service in the future, such as Bitcoin.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] Asset-backed tokens may have value because there is an underlying asset which the holder of the token can attribute value to.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] In many countries it is uncertain whether utility tokens require regulation, while it is more likely that asset-backed tokens do require regulation.
[src:tokenomics/initial-coin-offering] This makes it complex for the issuers of cryptocurrencies to analyze which countries their tokens (or coins) can be sold into, and for the prospective purchasers of cryptocurrencies to understand which regulations, if any, should apply.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] A **security token offering** (**STO**) **/ tokenized IPO** is a type of public offering in which tokenized digital securities, known as security tokens, are sold in security token exchanges.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Tokens can be used to trade real financial assets such as equities and fixed income, and use a blockchain virtual ledger system to store and validate token transactions.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Due to tokens being classified as securities, STOs are more susceptible to regulation and thus represent a more secure investment alternative than ICOs, which have been subject to numerous fraudulent schemes.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Furthermore, since ICOs are not held in traditional exchanges, they can be a less expensive funding source for small and medium-sized companies when compared to an IPO.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] An STO on a regulated stock exchange (referred to as a tokenized IPO) has the potential to deliver significant efficiencies and cost savings, however.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] By the end of 2019, STOs had been used in multiple scenarios including the trading of Nasdaq-listed company stocks, the pre-IPO of World Chess, FIDE's official broadcasting platform, and the creation of Singapore Exchange's own STO market, backed by Japan's Tokai Tokyo Financial Holdings.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Though sharing some core concepts with ICOs and IPOs, STOs are in fact different from both, standing as an intermediary model.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Similarly to ICOs, STOs are offerings that are made by selling digital tokens to the general public in cryptocurrency exchanges such as Binance, Kraken, Binaryx and others.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] The main difference stands in the fact that ICO tokens are the offered cryptocurrency's actual coins, entirely digital, and classified as utilities.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] New ICO currencies can be generated ad infinitum, as might in some cases their tokens.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Additionally, their value is almost entirely speculative and arises from the perceived utility value buyers expect them to provide.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Security tokens, on the other hand, are actual securities, like bonds or stocks, tied to a real company.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] In terms of legislation, some jurisdictions do treat STOs, ICOs, and other cryptocurrency-related operations under the same legislative umbrella.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] In general, though, STOs are placed under securities legislation (together with traditional IPOs), and ICOs under utilities, with the differentiation being made mostly on a case-by-case basis.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] The main debate surrounding security tokens is, thus, the legal differentiation of what can be qualified as a utility instead of a security.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Generally, legislation understands that if a passive financial return is expected from the investment, then it is classified as a security.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] This way, even if the offering company understands their tokens are merely a utility asset with no expected return investment, if it can be proven otherwise then the ICO becomes an unregulated STO, passive of legal punishment.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Moreover, this assumption of utility has been abused by some STO offering companies to sell securities without regulatory compliance (maliciously labeled as ICOs).
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] This legal ambiguity has led to some ICO offerers being prosecuted by the SEC as a security offering part, though their tokens were announced as utilities.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Such companies include messaging apps Kik and Telegram, the former being sued by the SEC for over $100 million and the latter delaying their offering plans after similar prosecution.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] One of the main selling points of cryptocurrencies such as Bitcoin has been the decentralization aspect, by which no government can influence or control the currency.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] By extension, a cryptocurrency is not directly affected by a specific country's jurisdiction, sociopolitical environment, or economic events.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Such a lack of regulation has led to the rising of large-scale crypto-related criminal activity, ranging from terrorist funding to tax evasion, most of which go untracked and unpunished.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] Similarly, ICO scams have been an increasingly troublesome matter, causing billions of dollars in losses and damaging the cryptocurrency market's value as a whole.
[src:tokenomics/security-token-offering] So far, STOs have been regulated and legalized in many countries where ICOs have not, due to fitting in many already pre-existing regulations regarding securities.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A **stablecoin** is a type of cryptocurrency that aims to maintain a stable value relative to a specified asset, a pool or basket of assets.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The specified asset might refer to fiat currency, commodity, or other cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Despite the name, stablecoins are not necessarily stable.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins rely on stabilization tools such as reserve assets or algorithms that match supply and demand to try to maintain a stable value.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Historically, multiple stablecoins have failed to maintain their value relative to the underlying assets.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] With a growing number of market transactions involving stablecoins, their issuance and usage are increasingly regulated by governments around the world.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins emerged in 2014 as a method for investors in cryptocurrencies to park their money when they invest in other highly volatile cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins are now mainly used for buying or selling cryptoassets, and for making cross-border payments.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to the Bank for International Settlements in July 2025, 90% of the market capitalization of stablecoins was either in Tether or USDC.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to the Financial Action Task Force, the market capitalization of stablecoins reached $316 billion in October 2025, while daily trading volume reached $156 billion.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Within the stablecoin market, 95% of them are backed by fiat currency, while 97% among those fiat currency-backed stablecoins are denominated in US dollar.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Fiat-backed stablecoins are stablecoins that are backed by assets denominated in a fiat currency.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The value of a fiat-backed stablecoin is based on the value of the backing currency, which is supposedly held by a third party custodian.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The issuer defends the peg of the stablecoin by holding mostly fiat-denominated short-term assets, such as treasury bonds, high-quality commercial paper, repurchase agreements and bank deposits.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Therefore, the structure of fiat-backed stablecoins closely resembles that of money market funds (MMFs), and they are exposed to similar risk of large-scale redemption requests causing negative contagion effects on the financial system.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] As of October 2025, nearly 97% of fiat-backed stablecoins are pegged to the US dollar.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Major examples of US-dollar-pegged stablecoins are Tether's USDT and Circle's USDC.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] For Euro-pegged stablecoins, examples include Circle's EURC, EUR Tether, and Stasis EUR.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Cryptocurrency-backed stablecoins are stablecoins using other cryptocurrencies as collateral.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The reason such stablecoins are created is that by utilizing smart contracts, they allow a decentralized network to track the price of the US dollar as closely as possible.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Another use case of cryptocurrency-backed stablecoins is to convert a cryptocurrency into ERC20 compatible standard to enable trading on another blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Commodity-backed stablecoins are stablecoins that are backed by commodities.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Algorithmic stablecoins, sometimes called seigniorage-style stablecoin, are stablecoins with no reserve assets or only partial reserve assets.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] They utilize algorithms that match supply and demand of the stablecoins to maintain a stable value.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The European Central Bank suggests that algorithmic stablecoins should be treated as unbacked crypto-assets.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Some major examples of algorithmic stablecoins are Celo Dollar, Tron's USDD and Kava's USDX.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins provide convenience for investors in cryptocurrencies, as a simpler way to buy and sell other more volatile cryptocurrencies.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] *Planet Money* has described this use of stablecoins as similar to casino chips, as they simplify buying and selling other cryptocurrencies before eventually being traded for money.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to a 2025 report from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), cross-border flows of stablecoin surpassed those of unbacked crypto assets in early 2022.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to the IMF, Asia and the Pacific region have the most stablecoin activity, while after adjusting for GDP, the majority of stablecoins flow from North America to other locations.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The report estimated that stablecoin cross-border flow was $1.4 trillion dollars in 2024, compared to the global cross-border payment market of approximately one quadrillion dollars.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In advanced economies, cross-border flows is dominated by traditional payment systems.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The largest share of stablecoins being used for cross-border transactions was among emerging markets and developing economies.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to a study by the University of Cambridge, the most cited reason for using stablecoins in cross-border settlement is the 24/7 settlement capability, allowing transactions to take place outside banking hours.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A 2025 study in the journal *Telematics and Informatics*, of 866 U.S.-based adults who had sent remittances within the previous year, 26% reported using stablecoins for cross-border transfers, with 34% also using other methods.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to Chainalysis, due to the volatility of the Venezuelan bolivar, some Venezuelans use US dollar-denominated stablecoins to preserve value and transact in a more stable currency.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In January 2026, it was reported that US dollar-denominated stablecoins are increasingly being used in domestic transactions in Venezuela due to prolonged period of hyperinflation, sanctions, and capital controls.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A report by Standard Chartered warned that the prevalence of US dollar-denominated stablecoins could potentially cause $1 trillion from developing countries to flow to stablecoins, causing loss of bank deposits.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The capital outflow would be caused by risk aversion of individuals within the developing countries against sudden sharp currency depreciation.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Since 2019, Oxfam began distributing humanitarian aid to residents of Vanutau using US dollar stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] By 2022, the project registered 35,000 people in the Pacific region and has distributed aid of around $2 million to participants.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to a report published by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in January 2026, the UNDP is running pilot programmes involving stablecoins in Columbia, Syria, Gambia, Papua New Guinea, Kazakhstan, and Morocco.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] For example, in Syria, the UNDP Cash-for-Work programmes experienced difficulty delivering stipends to Syrians due to lack of financial infrastructure, and so the UNDP is experimenting with sending stablecoins to the beneficiaries instead.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] According to media report in 2021, Portuguese nonprofit ImpactMarket reported distributing over $1 million in Celo Dollar stablecoins to more than 18,000 beneficiaries in 102 locations in Africa, and said some local merchants had begun accepting the tokens for payments.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In January 2024, the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) reported that stablecoins, particularly USDT, had become the cryptocurrency of choice for organized crime groups engaged in cyberfraud and money laundering in East and Southeast Asia.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Reuters reported in 2023 that groups designated as terrorist organizations by Israel, the United States and other countries were using stablecoins on the Tron blockchain instead of more volatile bitcoin tokens to preserve the value of transferred funds.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The intergovernmental Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has reported that stablecoins are increasingly used for illicit financial activity, including money laundering, terrorism financing, sanctions evasion, and proliferation financing.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The report states that stablecoins such as USDT (Tether) and USDC (Circle) provide a relatively stable medium for moving proceeds compared with more volatile cryptocurrencies, and that their liquidity, interoperability, and ease of cross-border transfer make them attractive for illicit use.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] After the passing of the GENIUS Act by the Trump administration in the United States, Jürgen Schaaf, adviser to the European Central Bank (ECB) wrote that widespread adoption of US dollar stablecoins could erode European monetary sovereignty and financial stability.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Scholars in China and Singapore have both described the GENIUS Act as a strategic move to increase demand for US Treasuries and therefore an attempt to consolidate the hegemony of the US dollar.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Lesetja Kganyago, Governor of South African Reserve Bank, expressed that US dollar stablecoins are being used to undermine African currencies, and is concerned that some African countries might lose their monetary sovereignty.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Agnès Bénassy-Quéré, Deputy Governor of the Banque de France, and François Villeroy de Galhau, Governor of the Banque de France, warned that Europe's monetary sovereignty is threatened by US dollar-denominated stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In March 2026, a research published by the ECB examined the effect of foreign-currency-denominated stablecoins on the monetary sovereignty of Europe.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The adoption of US dollar-denominated stablecoins would import foreign monetary policies into Europe, weakening the ability of central banks to affect short-term interest rates, complicate liquidity management within the banking system, and increase exchange-rate-related volatility in funding flows.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In extreme cases, it could make Europe's own monetary policy tools ineffective.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In response to sanctions against Russian entities, A7A5, a rouble-pegged stablecoin, was launched by Promsvyazbank and Moldovan oligarch Ilan Șor.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The stablecoin was used by Russian businesses to conduct cross-border payments and by the Russian state to carry out an influence campaign.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In October 2025, the UN's Multilateral Sanctions Monitoring Team found that North Korea avoided sanctions by using stablecoin for sale and transfer of military equipment and raw materials.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The report alleged that North Korean officials sold military-grade satellite communications systems to a buyer in Laos and a portable air defense system to a buyer in Sudan.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In January 2026, it was reported that the Central Bank of Iran is accumulating stablecoins while facing sanctions against the Iranian regime.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] While stablecoins aim to maintain the peg with underlying assets, they are constantly traded on the market and therefore subject to market volatility.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A stablecoin can deviate from the peg due to a number of reasons, such as liquidity stress, increase in market demand, mismanagement of reserves, fluctuations in prices of other cryptocurrencies, design flaws of stabilization mechanic, etc.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Since fiat-backed stablecoins are structurally similar to money market funds, they pose similar contagion risk, in which a large amount of redemption caused the selling of underlying assets, further pushing down the price of the underlying assets and creating more demand for redemption.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Partner banks of stablecoin issuers would also face substantial increase in liquidity risk exposure due to linkage with fiat-backed stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Unlike money market funds, stablecoins are designed to be settlement instruments, and therefore may face more rapid conversion, resulting in increased liquidity risk.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Reserve-backed stablecoins require a third party custodian to hold the reserve assets to maintain price stability.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The concentration of reserve deposits creates a counterparty risk in which the custodian may fail in the case of a bank run.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In March 2023, the price of Circle's USDC de-pegged temporarily during the banking crisis in the United States in which Signature Bank, Silvergate Bank, and Silicon Valley Bank collapsed.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Fiat-backed stablecoins maintain the peg with underlying currency by using reserve assets such as US Treasuries.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Since the value of Treasuries are affected by interest rate, it is possible for stablecoins to become insolvent when interest rate increase.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Some stablecoin issuers mitigate this risk by allocating the majority of their backing asset into short duration securities which are less affected by interest rate.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In an analysis on IMF's Finance & Development, Professor Hélène Rey wrote that advancement in quantum computing is often ignored in the discussion of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Quantum computers in the near future may be able to break public-key cryptography, allowing hackers to attack the currency networks used by stablecoins, potentially causing financial crises.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A research by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology pointed out that flaws in the logic of smart contracts could potentially result in stablecoin issuers losing control of the supply of stablecoins and their network.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Cross-chain bridges are another attack vector which can cause deposit and redemption issues.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Tether's USDT is currently the world's largest market capitalization stablecoin.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Tether initially claimed their stablecoin is fully backed by fiat currency.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] However, in October 2021, it failed to produce audits for reserves used to collateralize the quantity of minted USDT stablecoin.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Tether were fined $41 million by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) for deceiving consumers.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The CFTC found that Tether only had enough fiat reserves to guarantee their stablecoin for 27.6% of the time during 2016 to 2018.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Since then, Tether began issuing assurance reports on USDT backing, although some speculation persists regarding the use of Chinese commercial paper for reserves.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] As at February 2026, Tether had never completed an audit by an accounting firm.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Hyun-Song Shin, governor of the Bank of Korea, wrote in his research that since stablecoins on different blockchains are not interoperable, they create a fragmented ecosystem as compared to fiat money, which has the advantage of network effect.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The requirement of "gas fee" for transactions, and the increase in fee when traffic is high, creates a dilemma in which users are incentivized to switch to blockchains with lower fees, ensuring that the ecosystem is fragmented.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Algorithmic stablecoins are vulnerable to a de-pegging process known as "death spiral", in which an external event, such as the tightening of global liquidity, led to heavy redemption of the stablecoin.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] This triggered the minting of the linked token to burn the stablecoin, causing the supply of the linked token to increase exponentially, further causing a decrease in price.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A famous case of death spiral is the TerraUSD (UST), which was created by Terraform Labs founded by Do Kwon.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] TerraUSD was meant to maintain a 1:1 peg with the United States dollar.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Instead of being backed by dollars, UST was designed to keep its peg by linking it with another Terra network token, LUNA.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The mechanism worked by providing an economic incentive for arbitrage.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] If UST lost its peg and traded below $1, an arbitrager could purchase it on the secondary market and redeem it for $1 worth of LUNA.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Correspondingly, if UST traded higher than $1, market actors could mint new UST by locking in $1 of LUNA and then sell the new UST on the market for a profit.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] However, this mechanism assumes there is sufficient market demand for UST and LUNA, making the stablecoin inherently fragile.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In May 2022, UST broke its peg with its price plunging to 10 cents, while LUNA fell to "virtually zero", down from an all-time high of $119.51.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The collapse wiped out almost $45 billion of market capitalization over the course of a week.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In the case of TerraUSD, another contributing factor to its failure was its proof-of-stake mechanism.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The fall in the price of LUNA caused validators to sell their stakes, allowing malign actors to become dominant validators.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] A stablecoin should not be confused with a central bank digital currency (CBDC).
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] CBDC is issued by central banks, meaning that they are a direct claim on the central bank, while stablecoin is issued by private entity.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Another difference is that CBDC, being issued by central banks, would belong to the monetary base (M0), while stablecoins issued by commercial financial institutions would belong to the monetary aggregate (M2).
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The European Central Bank's digital euro project has been under consideration since 2021 but has not been legislated by the European Parliament as of August 2025.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Christine Lagarde, president of European Central Bank, called it a "strategic priority" for Europe in response to US legislation of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] While most stablecoins are non-interest bearing and therefore do not provide interest returns to the holder, some issuers and service providers began offering yield-bearing stablecoins in an attempt to gain market share.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The reason most stablecoins with centralized issuers do not provide interest return is because that would potentially make them financial securities, thus falling under regulatory regime.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The US's *GENIUS Act*, Europe's *MiCAR*, and Hong Kong's *Stablecoin Bill* all explicitly prohibit the provision of yield-bearing stablecoins by regulated issuers.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Australian regulator treats yield-bearing stablecoins as managed investment schemes.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In February 2026, media reported that legislation in the US regarding the provision of interest was stalled due to opposition from banks.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Some cryptoasset service providers (CASPs) such as trading platforms and market makers developed products for stablecoin users to earn interests.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] For example, a user can buy stablecoins through a trading platform and re-lent the bought stablecoins to the platform.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The platform then provides the stablecoins to institutional borrowers to earn interest.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The interest is passed to the user after subtracting the platform's margin.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The European Union and Hong Kong completely prohibit CASPs from offering yield on payment stablecoins, while Singapore restricted such products to institutional investors under limited conditions.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] While issuers may not directly provide interest return, decentralized financial platforms are another possible avenue for earning interests.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] By providing stablecoins for liquidity on decentralized platforms, holders of stablecoins can get a share of the fees paid by liquidity takers.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] This process is known as "yield farming".
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Contrary to popular belief, yield farming is not risk free, because the holders are engaged in lending activity.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In the case of the TerraUSD, initially to drive adoption, the Anchor protocol was created to offer a yield of 19.5% to depositors of the stablecoin, a rate much higher than the return on US Treasuries.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Thus, a large amount of the stablecoin is locked in the Anchor protocol.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Subsequently when the price of TerraUSD began to crash.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The holders are unable to cash out of their position and are left holding the bag.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The Central Bank of Armenia (CBA) has adopted the *Law on Crypto Assets* in 2025 to strengthen consumer protection in cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In addition, the CBA is trying to introduce regulations on issuance of stablecoins in 2026 with assistance from the IMF.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins in Australia are regulated by the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC).
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In December 2024, the ASIC published the "*Information Sheet 225 Crypto-assets*" (INFO 225), establishing the regulatory requirement of stablecoins under "*Corporations Act 2001*".
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Under the definition, issuers of stablecoin are treated as operating non-cash payment facilities; algorithmic stablecoins are treated as derivatives; while yield-bearing stablecoins are treated as managed investment schemes.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In September and December 2025, the ASIC issued exemptions to obtain licenses for intermediaries providing services related to stablecoins and distributing stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In July 2025, the Central Bank of Bahrain introduced the *Stablecoin Issuance and Offering (SIO) Module*.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Under the regulation, stablecoin issuers can issue single currency fiat-backed stablecoins pegged to the Bahraini Dinar, US dollar, or any other fiat currency upon obtaining approval of the central bank.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In November 2025, the Canadian government under Mark Carney announced in the Federal Budget 2025 of a proposed legislation to regulate the issuance of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The legislation is expected to require issuers to maintain asset reserves, govern redemption policies, implement risk management frameworks, and protect personal information of Canadians.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The *Retail Payment Activities Act* will also be amended to enable regulation of payment service providers using stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The proposed legislation was made in direct response to the United States' legislation of the *GENIUS Act*.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Stablecoins are considered illegal in Mainland China.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The People's Bank of China, the central bank of China, also asked Chinese companies, including Ant Group and JD.com, to stop their plans to issue stablecoins in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region in October 2025.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The central bank further clarified in November 2025 that stablecoins are considered non-compliant with current regulation and asked regulatory bodies and law enforcement to crackdown on the use of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In February 2026, the China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) issued a notice banning the issuance of Renminbi-denominated stablecoins within and outside China, the reason being that currency issuance is a matter of sovereignty.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The European Union introduced the *Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation* (MiCAR) in June 2023.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The regulation became applicable to asset-referenced tokens and e-money tokens on 30 June 2024.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] MiCAR has no clear regulation on global firms issuing the same stablecoin both from an EU-regulated entity and from a third-country entity, causing concern that in that event of large scale redemption of a multi-country stablecoin, the reserves located in the EU might be quickly depleted.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In September 2025, a consortium of nine European banks announced the planned launch of a MiCAR compliant stablecoin in response to the dominance of US denominated stablecoins on the market.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In December 2024, Hong Kong gazetted its *Stablecoins Bill*.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), the regulatory body of stablecoins in Hong Kong, warned the public to "rein in the euphoria".
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In particular, guidelines require stablecoin issuers to have strict rules on anti-money laundering, risk management, and corporate governance.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In April 2026, the HKMA issued stablecoin licenses to HSBC and Standard Chartered.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In June 2022, Japan's Financial Services Agency launched the *Regulatory Framework for Crypto-assets and Stablecoins*.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The regulation requires stablecoin issuer of fiat-backed stablecoin (known as digital-money type stablecoins in Japan) to register with the agency.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The agency views algorithmic stablecoin as crypto assets and does not require issuer to register.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] However, intermediaries such as crypto exchanges are subject to regulations.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In August 2025, fintech company JPYC received approval by the agency to launch the first stablecoin pegged to the Japanese Yen.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The first yen-pegged stablecoin launched in October 2025.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In November 2025, Kyrgyzstan launched the first national stablecoin, USDKG.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The issuer is state-owned company Virtual Asset Issuer OJSC.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The stablecoin is backed by gold and pegged to the US dollar.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In September 2025, the Central Bank of Russia approved the stablecoin A7A5 as a digital financial asset which can be used by Russian importers and exporters for cross-border settlements.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In November 2023, the Monetary Authority of Singapore finalized its *Stablecoin Regulatory Framework* after conducting public consultation since October 2022.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Issuers of stablecoins are required to maintain a portfolio of reserve assets denominated in the currency of the stablecoin peg.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] On 16 November 2023, the regulator approved Paxos Digital and StraitsX as stablecoin issuers.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Regulations on the issuance of stablecoins in South Korea are being discussed.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In February 2026, Bank of Korea, the central bank of South Korea, suggested that only licensed commercial banks should be able to issue won-denominated stablecoins to alleviate concerns regarding money laundering and financial stability.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] However, the Financial Services Commission (FSC) suggested a more open approach on the participation of technology firms, arguing that a rigid approach would hinder innovation.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In June 2024, the Central Bank of the UAE established the *Payment Token Services Regulations* to regulate the use of stablecoins in the UAE.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The regulations prohibit persons within the UAE from accepting stablecoins for the sale of goods and services except licensed payment token.In April 2025, the sovereign wealth fund of Abu Dhabi, ADQ, and the First Abu Dhabi Bank, are set to launch a stablecoin backed by dirhams.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In February 2026, the central bank approved the dirham-backed stablecoin launched by the First Abu Dhabi Bank.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In October 2025, Andrew Bailey, governor of the Bank of England, announced that the Bank of England will publish a consultation paper on the UK's stablecoin regulation.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The regulation is set to apply to stablecoins used for day-to-day payments and those used for settling tokenized financial transaction.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Bailey is known to be a skeptic of stablecoin and once said stablecoins risked pulling money out of the banking system.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] The comments by Bailey drawn criticism from stablecoin issuer for constraining investment in the UK.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] Under the proposed regulation, individuals would be subject to a limit of holding £20,000 worth of stablecoins.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In February 2026, the Financial Conduct Authority, Britain's financial regulator, announced the use of a "sandbox" programme to trial stablecoin products in controlled conditions.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In June 2026, lawmakers in the House of Lords called for a softer regulation on stablecoins, especially regarding the cap on the stablecoin holdings of individuals and requirement on issuers to back tokens with non-interest-bearing deposits.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In July 2025, the United States passed the *GENIUS Act*, a bill which allows banks and other financial institutions to issue stablecoins backed by fiat currency or other high-quality collateral, such as US Treasuries.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] At the time of its passing, the bill was expected to generate greater demand for US Treasuries by stablecoin issuers.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In November 2025, Stephen Miran at the Federal Reserve Board of Governors, confirmed that stablecoins are already increasing demand for US Treasuries, and are "contributing to the dollar's dominance".
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] This would cause a decrease in the neutral rate of interest and lower borrowing cost for the US government.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] An estimate by the Bank for International Settlements using data from 2021 to 2025 found that demand for stablecoins lowers 3-month T-bill yields by about 2-2.5 basis points, an effect comparable to that of small-scale quantitative easing.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In March 2023, the Legislature of the State of Wyoming passed the *Wyoming Stable Token Act*, which established the Wyoming Stable Token Commission for the purpose of issuing stablecoin.
[src:tokenomics/stablecoin] In January 2026, the first state-backed stablecoin has been released in Wyoming.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] The field often has a strong applied focus, concerning itself with how to use its insights and principles to engineer economic systems to possess specific, desired properties.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Both cryptocurrency and tokens are the subclasses of digital assets that use the technology of cryptography.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Cryptocurrency is the native currency of a blockchain, while tokens are created as part of a platform that is built on an existing blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Tokens can be created as native elements of a blockchain protocol, or by using a smart contract that is deployed on a blockchain which will host the new token.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] For example, Ether (ETH) is the native crypto asset of the Ethereum blockchain, and was created by the core Ethereum developer team to incentivise proper maintenance of the blockchain.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] While Axie Infinity Shards (AXS) tokens, were created using an Ethereum smart contract developed by an unaffiliated third party, in order to give token holders certain governance rights over the game Axie Infinity.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In both cases, different tokenomic attributes are chosen to support the token's intended role.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] With particular attention typically being paid to tokens' ability to function as an incentive mechanism, and choosing monetary policy that brings token supply into line with its demand.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] This includes specifying rules about how and when new token should be generated or removed from the system.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Rules that are written into smart contracts allow these system processes to be automated.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In the real-world economics system, the economy is subject to fluctuations like inflation and deflation.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Central banks intervene through monetary policies.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Tokenomics can be thought of as an approach to implementing monetary policies and economic rules via automated smart contracts.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] On the blockchain, different projects may issue their own tokens with different tokenomics to complete their ecosystem for various purposes, such as fundraising and governance.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Some common tokenomics models include the deflationary model, inflationary model, and dual-token model.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] For instance, before the very last Bitcoin is added to the Bitcoin pool, it is inflationary because as miners (people who find Bitcoin by using algorithms to solve mathematical puzzles) keep mining Bitcoins, the amount of Bitcoins increases and the purchasing power of each Bitcoin decrease.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] However, the tokenomics of Bitcoin has multiple mechanisms to lower the rate of inflation, such as making mathematical puzzles harder and harder to solve and allowing fewer and fewer miners to receive the coin.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Companies may create their own tokens for economic and structural reasons.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Tokens are created to encourage the holder to interact with and empower the product by distributing the tokens to their stakeholders as rewards or means of incentivization.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Projects may use tokens to raise funds from the public and for proof of internal operation (e.g. game tokens and governance tokens for the right to vote).
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] To achieve the purposes and function of the tokens created, a fine tokenomics structure is needed.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In traditional capital markets, if a company wants to raise funds from the public, it must go through an initial public offering (IPO), which may take years, costing anywhere from $4 to $28 million in fees, depending on its size.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In the early stages, only accredited investors are allowed to enter an investment, such as a venture capital.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In the decentralized, automated world, with lower cost, tokens can be created by anyone, with fundamental parameters and functions described by tokenomics.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Instead of equities, blockchain companies raise funds through the issuing of tokens in the process of initial coin offerings (ICOs).
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] The security tokens can be thought of as equity shares of the blockchain companies.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] After issuing the tokens, individual investors are allowed to buy tokens and own shares.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] For investors, they can become early contributors to gain returns along with the growth of the company.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Web 3.0 investors can sell their holdings of tokens after the vesting period.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Utility tokens are used as proof to access a company's service or product.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Unlike security tokens, utility tokens are for exchange and securing the liquidity and value of the company.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Utility tokens are an in-ecosystem currency.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] For example, with a token named Smooth Love Potion (SLP) in the game Axie Infinity, players can use it to breed desired spirits.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] In this case, SLP acts as the internal currency within the game.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Users earn SLP from tasks, and spend SLP to defeat opponents.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Investors risk being "rugged," meaning that the token issuer may "raise money and disappear," resulting in a value loss in those tokens and a capital loss for investors.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Hackers may hack into the system and steal the tokens.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Another risk could be the bad management of the market from the team and an excessive inflation or deflation of the token itself.
[src:tokenomics/tokenomics] Each tokenomics model has its disadvantages and advantages.
